The usual construction of sinc-sive, as of our disjunctives ‘whether-or,’ is that each has a verb to itself in protasis, while the apodosis consists of one single verb, which is applicable to ' both or more alternatives. Thus Plaut. Trin. 1. r. 146 seu recte scu perverse sacta sunt, Egomet fecisse confiteor. ‘Whether it was well or badly done, I confess that 1 did it! In the passage before us, each fresh alternative introduced by sinc has an apodosis of its own, so that the sense is not represented by ‘whether —or—-or,' but by ‘If—or if-if again,’ etc. See Ovid.
